g.text: Traffic Manager
Project Manager
Port Manager
Client
Ship Captain
Port Staff
Ship Chief Electrical Engineer
US101: Import ships from a text file into a BST
US102: Search the details of a ship using any of its codes: MMSI, IMO or Call Sign
US103: Have the positional messages temporally organized and associated with each of the ships
US104: Make a summary of a ship's movements
US105: List for all ships the MMSI, the total number of movements, Travelled Distance and Delta Distance

US108: Develop the data model required to support all the functionality and to fulfill the purpose of the system to develop. This data model is to be designed following a systematic data modeling methodology
US109: Draft an SQL script to test whether the database verifies all the data integrity restrictions that are required to fulfil the purpose of the system and the business constraints of the UoD

US110: Define the naming conventions to apply when defining identifiers or writing SQL or PL/SQL code. The naming conventions may evolve as new database and programming objects are known. The naming conventions guide should be organized in a way to facilitate its maintenance

US111: Create a SQL script to load the database with a minimum set of data sufficient to carry out data integrity verification and functional testing. This script shall produce a bootstrap report providing the number of tuples/rows in each relation/table
US201: Import ports from a text file and create a 2D-tree with port locations
US202: Find the closest port of a ship given its CallSign, on a certain DateTime
US203: Review the relational data model in view of the new user stories so it can support all the requirements to fulfil the purpose of the system being developed
US204: Know the current situation of a specific container being used to transport my goods
US205: List of containers to be offloaded in the next port, including container identifier, type, position, and load
US206: List of containers to be loaded in the next port, including container identifier, type, and load
US207: Know how many cargo manifests I have transported during a given year and the average number of containers per manifest

US208: Know the occupancy rate (percentage) of a given ship for a given cargo manifest. Occupancy rate is the ratio between total number of containers in the ship coming from a given manifest and the total capacity of the ship, i.e., the maximum number of containers the ship can load
US209: Know the occupancy rate of a given ship at a given moment
US210: Know which ships will be available on Monday next week and their location
US301: Import data from countries, ports, borders and seadists files to build a freight network.
US302: Colour the map using as few colours as possible.
US303: Know which places (cities or ports) are closest to all other places (closeness places).

US304: Have access to audit trails for a given container of a given cargo manifest, that is, I want to have access to a list of all operations performed on a given container of a given manifest, in chronological order.
US305: Know the route of a specific container I am leasing.
US306: Know the occupancy rate of each warehouse and an estimate of the containers leaving the warehouse during the next 30 days.
US307: Get a warning whenever I issue a cargo manifest destined for a warehouse whose available capacity is insufficient to accommodate the new manifest.
US308: Have a system that ensures that the number of containers in a manifest does not exceed the ship's available capacity.
US309: not allow a cargo manifest for a particular ship to be registered in the system on a date when the ship is already occupied.
US310: Have a map of the occupation of the existing resources in the port during a given month.
US311: Provide a database access account, with login “crew” and password “bd7wd5aF”, which gives access exclusively to the information of the containers that are loaded on my ship.
US312: Know the current situation of a specific container being used to transport my goods - US204.
US313: Given a Cargo Manifest, I wish to fill a statically reserved matrix in memory with each container's ID in its respective place.
US314: Know the total number of free/occupied slots in the transport vehicle.
US315: Given a position in the transport vehicle, I wish to know if a container is there or not.
US316: Given a set of positions, I wish to know the total number of occupied slots.
US317: Know what set of materials to use in a container, to operate at temperatures of 7°C.
US318: Know what set of materials to use in a container, to operate at temperatures of -5 °C.

US319: Know the thermal resistance, for each operating temperature, of each container that must contain at least three different materials in its walls. One for the outer wall, one for the intermediate material, and one for the inner wall.
US320: Present in a summary document, the choice of materials considered for the two types of containers considered, and their thermal resistances.
